{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"056951df-7e39-428b-b4c2-14ac66d7ea93","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet in this workspace, but I can tell you exactly what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a dotnet tool:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <!-- Makes it a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n\n  <!-- The command users will run (e.g., `dotnet tool install -g my-mcp-server`) -->\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- Must be Exe for stdio transport -->\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server   # runs via stdio\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- `PackAsTool` + `OutputType=Exe` are the critical settings\n- `ToolCommandName` controls the CLI command name\n- No `PackageReference` changes needed — your existing MCP SDK references will be bundled automatically","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d13de01e-adaf-44b7-9ded-c77546811234","outputTokens":473,"requestId":"3C00:1C7D40:1F06B48:22F3532:69E81D55"},"id":"1798324c-0918-4ce1-ace7-1ca7d8fdcb11","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:59:11.440Z","parentId":"7aa2b95e-5fa4-41a0-baff-d94aff175a11"}
